      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i checked the fuel pressure and it's within spec. injectors look okay too. i'm starting to think it might be a vacuum leak somewhere in the intake manifold or maybe a cracked hose. how can i properly test for a leak without just spraying everything with brake cleaner and hoping for the best?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, a vacuum leak, you say? A sneaky little troublemaker indeed. If you suspect a vacuum leak, you can try a more systematic approach. First, visually inspect the intake manifold and all the hoses for any obvious signs of damage or cracks. If you don't see anything, you can use a smoke machine to introduce smoke into the vacuum system. The smoke will escape from any leaks, making them visible. Alternatively, you can use a spray bottle with a light-colored liquid, like soapy water, and spray it along the intake manifold and hoses while the engine is running. If you see any bubbles forming, that's a good indication of a leak. Remember, it's always better to be thorough and leave no stone unturned. Good luck, and may the winds of fortune be in your favor!",
